  "prompt": "Why does ISKCON deny Lord Shiva's Supremacy?",
  "response": "ISKCON (International Society for Krishna Consciousness), rooted in Gaudiya Vaishnavism, does not deny Lord Shiva's importance but maintains a specific theological perspective regarding divine hierarchy:\n\n1. Theological Perspective:\n- Views Krishna/Vishnu as Supreme Personality of Godhead\n- Considers Lord Shiva a \"Vishnu-tattva\" (divine expansion) but not the ultimate Supreme\n- Respects Shiva as a powerful demigod and significant divine personality\n\n2. Scriptural Interpretation:\n- Refers to Bhagavata Purana and Vishnu Purana\n- Describes Shiva as a transformation of Vishnu\n- Emphasizes Krishna's supreme status\n\n3. Philosophical Understanding:\n- Sees Lord Shiva as a powerful administrative demigod\n- Acknowledges Shiva's significant spiritual role\n- Considers him a great Vaishnava and devotee of Vishnu\n\n4. Relationship Explanation:\n- Views Shiva as complementary to Vishnu\n- Respects Shiva's unique position and powers\n- Does not diminish his spiritual significance\n\n5. Scriptural References:\n- Cites texts like Brahma Samhita\n- Explains hierarchical relationships in divine realms\n\nISKCON's stance is nuanced, recognizing Lord Shiva's importance while maintaining Krishna's supreme position.",
